update How to Create an Emergency Fund section as follows:
Building an emergency fund isn’t optional — it’s your financial shield against life’s unexpected punches (job loss, medical bills, car repairs). Here’s the no-nonsense way to do it right:
1.  List out ALL your expenses Track every naira/dollar you spend for 1-2 months. Be brutally honest — rent, food, transport, subscriptions, everything.
2.  Separate discretionary from essential expenses Essentials: Rent, groceries, utilities, minimum debt payments, transportation. Discretionary: Eating out, entertainment, shopping, luxuries. Cut the fat here first.
3.  Open a dedicated Savings or Money Market Fund Park it somewhere liquid, safe, and separate from your daily spending account. Target: Save 3-6 months of your essential expenses as the minimum. Aim higher (6-12 months) if you’re self-employed or in a volatile industry.
Start small if you must — even ₦10k/$50 weekly adds up. Automate the transfers so you don’t “forget.”
Your emergency fund = sleeping better at night. No more panic borrowing or selling assets at a loss.
